- "blooming with multiple versions" refers to components having more than one distinct version;
- "recently visited" refers to components accessed after January 1, 2023;
- "caught the attention of more than a handful of users" refers to components accessed by more than two distinct users.

- "popular" refers to components with the highest number of access events;
- "access" includes both view and edit types;
- "top 5" means the five components with the highest access counts.

- 'Released' refers to components that have been officially made available;
- 'Viewed by users' indicates that users have accessed these components;
- 'Measured in milliseconds' means the parameters associated with these components are measured using the unit 'Milliseconds' with the symbol 'ms'.

- Top-level components are those not categorized as 'Sub-components';
- 'Released' parameter versions are those with a version status of 'released';
- 'Milliseconds' is a unit of time measurement.

- 'latest flowers' refers to the most recent version of the component;
- 'diligent designers' refers to users with the 'designer' role;
- 'stands out as the most frequently visited' refers to the highest number of access events by designers.

- 'Bob Williams' is a specific user in the system;
- 'version_number' refers to the version of the component;
- 'access_count' is the number of times a user accessed a component;
- 'avg_component_access' is the average number of times the component was accessed by all users.

- "Visited a component" refers to accessing the component in the `access_logs` table;
- "Blossomed into its latest version" refers to the latest version number in the `component_versions` table;
- "Recently" indicates that the access date is after the latest version creation date;
- "Designers" refers to users with the role 'designer' in the `roles` table.

- 'Caught the eye of the engineers' refers to components that have been accessed by users with the 'engineer' role;
- 'More than once' means the component has been accessed more than one time;
- 'Details of their released versions' include the version number, version description, and version date.

- "Components" refer to parts or elements in a system or application;
- "Accessed" refers to the number of times a component has been used or interacted with;
- "Popularity" is determined by the frequency of access.

- "Minimum parameter value" refers to the lowest value that a specific parameter can take for a component;
- "Average minimum parameter value" is the mean of these minimum values across different versions of the same component;
- "Above the threshold of zero" means that the average minimum parameter value is greater than zero;
- "Most substantial to least" indicates the order of the results, with the highest average minimum parameter value first.

- 'jewel in the crown' is a metaphor for the most valuable or important part of something;
- The 'designers' are users with the role 'designer';
- 'turn to the most often' refers to the most frequently accessed component.

- "blossomed through multiple versions" refers to having more than one version of their parameters;
- "frequently visited" means the component has been accessed more than once;
- "at least one gardener making changes" means the component has had at least one edit access.

- 'Most versions' refers to the component that has undergone the most updates or revisions;
- 'Most parameters' refers to the component that has the most configurable settings or attributes;
- 'Access events' refer to the number of times a component has been accessed or used;
- 'Beloved by the engineers' refers to components that are frequently accessed by users with the 'engineer' role.

- "intricate gems" refers to components with the highest parameter count;
- "gardeners" refers to users with specific roles;
- "tended to" means accessed or worked with the components.

- 'Temperature and Humidity' sensors are a sub-category of 'Sensors';
- 'designer' is a role that can be found in the `users` table;
- 'typical value' refers to a standard or common value of a parameter associated with a component.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT component_id) AS released_components_count
FROM component_versions
WHERE version_status = 'released';
